can i use cover or contain for an next Image?

Yes, you can use either cover or contain for an Next.js Image.

object-fit: cover will scale the image to fill the entire container, cropping the image if necessary to preserve the aspect ratio.

object-fit: contain will scale the image to fit within the container, preserving the aspect ratio. If the image is larger than the container, it will be letterboxed.

To use cover or contain, you can either set the objectFit prop on the Image component, or use the style prop to set the object-fit CSS property.

For example, to use cover for an Image component, you could do the following:

JavaScript
<Image
  src="/image.jpg"
  objectFit="cover"
  alt="A beautiful image"
/>
Use o código com cuidado. Saiba mais

Or, to use contain for an Image component, you could do the following:

JavaScript
<Image
  src="/image.jpg"
  style={{ objectFit: "contain" }}
  alt="A beautiful image"
/>
Use o código com cuidado. Saiba mais

Which option you choose will depend on the desired effect. If you want the image to fill the entire container, even if it means cropping the image, then you should use cover. If you want the image to fit within the container without being cropped, even if it means letterboxing the image, then you should use contain.

Here is a table that summarizes the difference between cover and contain:

OptionDescription
coverScales the image to fill the entire container, cropping the image if necessary to preserve the aspect ratio.
containScales the image to fit within the container, preserving the aspect ratio. If the image is larger than the container, it will be letterboxed.

I hope this helps!

To navigate to section 2 when the user clicks on the Saiba mais button, you can use the useRouter hook from Next.js.

First, import the useRouter hook:

JavaScript
import { useRouter } from "next/router";

Then, in your Home component, add the following code:

JavaScript
const Home = () => {
  const router = useRouter();

  const handleSaibaMaisClick = () => {
    router.push("/#section__2");
  };

  return (
    <main className={styles.main}>
      ...

      <section className={styles["section__1"]}>
        <div>
          <h1>Escritório de advocacia BR</h1>
          <div className={styles["s1__subtitle"]}>
            <h3>DIREITO IMOBILIÁRIO</h3>
          </div>
          <button className="btn__blue" onClick={handleSaibaMaisClick}>
            Saiba mais
          </button>
        </div>
        <Image src="" alt="img-s1" width={450} height={450} />
      </section>

      ...
    </main>
  );
};
Use o código com cuidado. Saiba mais

This code will use the useRouter hook to get the current router object. Then, when the user clicks on the Saiba mais button, the handleSaibaMaisClick function will be called. This function will use the router.push() method to navigate to the section__2 element on the page.

Note that the router.push() method will cause a full page refresh. If you want to avoid this, you can use the router.replace() method instead. However, this method will not update the browser history, so the user will not be able to use the back button to go back to the previous page.

Here is an example of how to use the router.replace() method:

JavaScript
const handleSaibaMaisClick = () => {
  router.replace("/#section__2");
};
